      • areAmbiguousHits

        public static boolean areAmbiguousHits(java.util.ArrayList<LSIClass> lsiClasses)
        Checks, if multiple hits are ambiguous results. They are ambiguous, if two or more of the hits of the list are not explicitly marked as 'different' by a 'DIFFER=' statment. If true, it is necessary either to eliminiate the ambiguity by 'WIN=', 'WIN=*' or 'LOSE=*' statements, or indicate that the ambiguity is based on real two objects classes using 'DIFFERS=' statments.
        Parameters:
        lsiClasses - list of LSI classes
        Returns:
        true if hits are ambiguous results

      • def

        public static void def(java.lang.String classToken,
                       java.lang.String superClassToken,
                       int lsiClassNrOffset,
                       int maximumSubclasses,
                       java.lang.String className,
                       java.lang.String simplifiedName,
                       java.lang.String[] synonymNames,
                       java.lang.String iconImage,
                       int dorendaFlags,
                       java.lang.String OSMtags,
                       java.lang.String geomTypes,
                       java.lang.String closedLineType)
        Defines a new LSI class without properties.
        Parameters:
        classToken - token for this class
        superClassToken - name of the upper class or "" (not null) for top-level classes
        lsiClassNrOffset - either the first digit lsiClass number (if top-level) or the lower digits, added to the upper class number. If 0, the system defines a number
        maximumSubclasses - typicall 10, but also 100, 1000 possible, 0 means: this class must be a class without any subclasses
        className - a user readable name
        simplifiedName - a simplified user readable name
        synonymNames - a list of user readable synonym names - these are the searchable strings by the symbole search services. [0] array means NOT searable. null object means, the class name is used
        iconImage - the name of the icon image without path and .png
        dorendaFlags - flags to control map rendering (constants see LSIClass)
        OSMtags - sequence of key==value, key!=value, key~=value, separated by ",", right-hand-side "*" allowed, also key=={value1, value2} or key!={value1, value2}. Komma-separated expressions (considered as AND) can be combinded by || (considered as OR). key!= means: there has to be such a key; ~= this key has not to appear, but if must be unequal to the given values. The special value 'IGNORE' is similar to the empty string, but suppresses a warning. 'IGNORE' is used for LSIClasses that are not set by an OSM tag condition. 'WIN=<class1>,<class2>,...;' is used to express that this class should be used as hit rather than <class1>, <class2>..., also +<class> is allowed to express that the entire subtree is beaten. 'WIN=*;' indicates that this class always wins against another hit. 'LOSE=<class1>,<class2>,...;' is opposite to 'WIN=' (also 'LOSE=*;'allowed). Note: 'WIN=*' and LOSE='<class1>,<class2>,...;' can be combined and vice versa. Then, the explicit list is used to reduce the '=*'. 'DIFFERS=<class1>, <class2>...; suppresses a warning if this class and class1... are multiple results of a same query (also DIFFERS=* is allowed, also +<class> is allowed which means <class> and all of its subclasses).
        geomTypes - string of "P" (point), "L" (open line), "A" (area or closed line), "R" (relation) e.g "PLA", "L". "*" is equal to "PLA"
        closedLineType - "R": a closed line is considered as ring, "A" a closed line is considered as area

      • format

        public static java.lang.String format(int lsiClass,
                                      java.lang.String realname,
                                      java.lang.String formatNoClassNoRealname,
                                      java.lang.String formatNoClass,
                                      java.lang.String formatNoRealname,
                                      java.lang.String formatRealnameIncludesClass,
                                      java.lang.String formatStandard)
        Creates string from LSI class and realname in a printf manner. This is useful, whenever a short description of a geo object has to be printed, e.g. "Restaurant Las Lunas". There exist some combination that make the printing complex, e.g. either class or name were not available. A special case: the realname incluces the class: if not considered, odd printings such as "Restaurant 'Restauraunt Las Lunas'" may result. To deal with this, the caller can pass up to five format strings. If null formats are passed, the next 'better' format is used. A format is an arbitrary string, that may contain some placeholders:
        • %lsinr: LSI class number (e.g. 16200000)
        • %lsito: LSI class 'to' number (e.g. 16299999)
        • %token: LSI class token (e.g. "GRENZE")
        • %Class: LSI class name i.e. its description (e.g. "Grenze (unspezifiziert)")
        • %csimp: LSI class name simplified) (e.g. "Grenze")
        • %rname: the geoobject's realname
        Parameters:
        lsiClass - the lsi class number
        realname - the geo object's realname. May be null, if there is no useful name available. It depends on the caller to decide this.
        formatNoClassNoRealname - format string, if no lsi class was available for the given number and the realname was null. Format may also be null.
        formatNoClass - format string, if no lsi class was available for the given number and the realname was available. Format may also be null.
        formatNoRealname - format string, if an lsi class was available for the given number and the realname was null. Format may also be null.
        formatRealnameIncludesClass - format string if both lsi class and realname were available, but the realname includes the class description or one if its synononyms, e.g. class="Steakhouse" and realname="Steakhouse Red Bull". Format may also be null.
        formatStandard - format string if both lsi class and realname were available, but the realname does not include the class description, e.g. class="Steakhouse" and realname="Red Bull". Format may notbe null.
        Returns:
        string

      • format1

        public static java.lang.String format1(int lsiClass,
                                       java.lang.String realname)
        Returns a string from LSI class and realname (that may be null). A format() call with predefined format strings, usually it outputs 
        class 'realname'
        , e.g. 
        Dorf 'Sulzbach'
        . The string is one of these cases
        • '???' if the object neither has an LSI type nor realname
        • 'realname' (in single quotes), if the object only has a realname
        • the simplified class name, if the object only has an LSI class
        • class name, 'realname', if the object has both and the realname does not include the class name
        • 'realname', if the object has both and the realname includes the class name
        Parameters:
        lsiClass - the lsi class number
        realname - the geo object's realname. May be null, if there is no useful name available. It depends on the caller to decide this.
        Returns:
        string

      • format2

        public static java.lang.String format2(int lsiClass,
                                       java.lang.String realname)
        Returns a string from LSI class and realname (that may be null). A format() call with predefined format strings, usually it outputs 
        realname (class)
        , e.g. 
        Sulzbach (Dorf)
        . The string is one of these cases
        • '???' if the object neither has an LSI type nor realname
        • 'realname' (in single quotes), if the object only has a realname
        • the simplified class name, if the object only has an LSI class
        • realname (class name), if the object has both and the realname does not include the class name
        • 'realname', if the object has both and the realname includes the class name
        Parameters:
        lsiClass - the lsi class number
        realname - the geo object's realname. May be null, if there is no useful name available. It depends on the caller to decide this.
        Returns:
        string
